3 Published CMIP6Plus BC True published Differences with CMIP6-1-2: The dataset contains data until December 2022 based on GFED4s Global Fire Emissions. Furthermore CO2 has been added as separate species. This dataset has been developed for the testing phase of CMIP7. DRES-CMIP-BB4CMIP7-2-0 extends the data to 2023. Modellers are advised to use DRES-CMIP-BB4CMIP7-2-0. Tables for validation of the data of various species, geographical areas and sectors can be found on https://www.geo.vu.nl/~gwerf/GFED/GFED4/tables/ for the 1997 onwards period. CR-CMIP-0-3-0 zebedee.nicholls@climate-resource.com;malte.meinshausen@climate-resource.com None GHGConcentrations mon http://www.tbd.invalid gm CR CC BY 4.0 atmos 0.3.0 CMIP 000101-202212
712 Published CMIP6Plus ccl4 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 775 Published CMIP6Plus cf4 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 811 Published CMIP6Plus cfc11 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 856 Published CMIP6Plus cfc113 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 892 Published CMIP6Plus cfc114 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 973 Published CMIP6Plus cfc115 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1009 Published CMIP6Plus cfc11eq True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1054 Published CMIP6Plus cfc12 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1090 Published CMIP6Plus cfc12eq True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). CR-CMIP-0-3-0 zebedee.nicholls@climate-resource.com;malte.meinshausen@climate-resource.com None GHGConcentrations mon http://www.tbd.invalid gnz CR CC BY 4.0 atmos 0.3.0 CMIP 000101-202212
1171 Published CMIP6Plus ch3br True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). CR-CMIP-0-3-0 zebedee.nicholls@climate-resource.com;malte.meinshausen@climate-resource.com None GHGConcentrations mon http://www.tbd.invalid gm CR CC BY 4.0 atmos 0.3.0 CMIP 000101-202212
1242 Published CMIP6Plus ch3cl True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1260 Published CMIP6Plus ch3cl True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1296 Published CMIP6Plus ch4 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1377 Published CMIP6Plus co2 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). CR-CMIP-0-3-0 zebedee.nicholls@climate-resource.com;malte.meinshausen@climate-resource.com None GHGConcentrations yr http://www.tbd.invalid gr1z CR CC BY 4.0 atmos 0.3.0 CMIP 0001-2022
1413 Published CMIP6Plus co2 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1448 Published CMIP6Plus halon1211 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1466 Published CMIP6Plus halon1211 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). CR-CMIP-0-3-0 zebedee.nicholls@climate-resource.com;malte.meinshausen@climate-resource.com None GHGConcentrations mon http://www.tbd.invalid gnz CR CC BY 4.0 atmos 0.3.0 CMIP 000101-202212
1502 Published CMIP6Plus halon1301 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1538 Published CMIP6Plus halon2402 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1583 Published CMIP6Plus hcc140a True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1611 Published CMIP6Plus hcfc141b True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1647 Published CMIP6Plus hcfc142b True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1728 Published CMIP6Plus hfc125 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1764 Published CMIP6Plus hfc125 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1845 Published CMIP6Plus hfc134aeq True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1881 Published CMIP6Plus hfc143a True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1962 Published CMIP6Plus hfc227ea True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 1998 Published CMIP6Plus hfc23 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 2079 Published CMIP6Plus hfc236fa True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 2115 Published CMIP6Plus hfc245fa True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 2151 Published CMIP6Plus hfc32 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. 2160 Published CMIP6Plus hfc32 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 2196 Published CMIP6Plus hfc365mfc True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 2232 Published CMIP6Plus hfc4310mee True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. 2274 Published CMIP6Plus n2o True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 2318 Published CMIP6Plus nd True published v2.0.0 includes the following key updates: i) new H2SO4 number density variable replacing aerosol number density; ii) correction to the 1920-1978 ice-core dataset, improving consistency with pyrheliometer measurements and CMIP6. 2321 Published CMIP6Plus nf3 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 2357 Published CMIP6Plus nf3 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. 2420 Published CMIP6Plus pfc5114 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 2440 Published CMIP6Plus pfc7118 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). CR-CMIP-0-3-0 zebedee.nicholls@climate-resource.com;malte.meinshausen@climate-resource.com None GHGConcentrations mon http://www.tbd.invalid gm CR CC BY 4.0 atmos 0.3.0 CMIP 000101-202212
2493 Published CMIP6Plus sf6 True published CR-CMIP-1-0-0 switches to much more conventional naming for gases. The affected gases are: c2f6 (previously pfc116), c3f8 (pfc218), c4f10 (pfc3110), c5f12 (pfc4112), c6f14 (pfc5114), c7f16 (pfc6116), c8f18 (pfc7118), cc4f8 (pfc318) and ch3ccl3 (hcc140a). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). A DOI is now also included in each file. Please use it so we can track usage of these files. In terms of science, CR-CMIP-1-0-0 updates to the latest ice core and AGAGE data, as well as using better data sources for HFC23, CF4, C2F6 and C3F8 than CR-CMIP-0-4-0. CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). CR-CMIP-1-0-0 also provides a smoother transition from ice core based records to more recent records (i.e. flask and in-situ samples) and more sensible pre-industrial values for gases with non-zero pre-industrial concentrations. It also uses the Scripps CO2 record to handle the period from 1959 to the start of the flask and in-situ samples from other networks. The CR-CMIP-1-0-0 dataset also provides much better information about the original data sources. As a result, CR-CMIP-0-4-0 is deprecated. For the full CHANGELOG, see [here](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP-GHG-Concentration-Generation/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md). For basic analysis of the changes between versions, see [this repo](https://github.com/climate-resource/CMIP6-vs-CMIP7-GHG-Concentrations). 2621 Retracted CMIP6Plus multiple False retracted v4.4 uses the final, absolute TSI scale (in consonance with NNL1) which should be used in CMIP7. Hence v4.3 is retracted. The change between v4.3 and v4.4 results in a 179 ppm increase of TSI and SSI compared to version 4.3. The preliminary TSI/SSI version in 4.3 had adapted the TSI scale from the CTIM instrument alone, the newer TSI scale is based on a TSIS-1 and CTIM composite (Coddington and Lean, 2024). This composite is also consistent with the TSI 'community consensus' composite (spot.colorado.edu/~koppg/TSI/TSI_Composite-SIST.txt). The original comment from the data provider is here. For further information, see SOLARIS-HEPPA release notes. 2624 Retracted CMIP6Plus multiple False retracted v4.4 uses the final, absolute TSI scale (in consonance with NNL1) which should be used in CMIP7. Hence v4.3 is retracted. The change between v4.3 and v4.4 results in a 179 ppm increase of TSI and SSI compared to version 4.3. The preliminary TSI/SSI version in 4.3 had adapted the TSI scale from the CTIM instrument alone, the newer TSI scale is based on a TSIS-1 and CTIM composite (Coddington and Lean, 2024). This composite is also consistent with the TSI 'community consensus' composite (spot.colorado.edu/~koppg/TSI/TSI_Composite-SIST.txt). The original comment from the data provider is here. For further information, see SOLARIS-HEPPA release notes. SOLARIS-HEPPA-CMIP-4-3 bernd@iaa.es None solar fx http://solarisheppa.geomar.de/cmip7 gn SOLARIS-HEPPA CC BY 4.0 atmos 4.3 CMIP None
2625 Retracted CMIP6Plus multiple False retracted v4.5 resolves issues with MEE short-term variability. Hence v4.4 is retracted. There are no changes to SSI/TSI (so, if you have used v4.4 for SSI/TSI, you do not need to restart). The original comment from the data provider is here.
